# Never Guess Content

Use only the content the user or source material provides. Do not invent, expand, polish, or substitute text, labels, placeholders, or answers.

## Hard Rules

- Copy text exactly as given — same words, same length, same punctuation. No paraphrasing, no "improving" placeholder copy, no adding extra sentences.
- If a Figma frame shows `Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet`, use exactly that string — not a longer lorem block, not real marketing copy, not a shortened version.
- If a design, spec, CMS field, or user message omits content, leave it out or ask — do not fill the gap with plausible guesses.
- If requirements, behavior, or intent are ambiguous, ask a clarifying question before proceeding. Do not assume and implement.
- Do not guess answers to technical or product questions. Say what is known from the codebase or source; ask when it is not known.

## When Content Is Missing

1. Check whether the source (Figma, Strapi, spec, ticket) actually provides the value.
2. If missing and blocking, ask the user one focused question with concrete options when helpful.
3. If missing and non-blocking, use an explicit placeholder only when the project already defines one — otherwise omit or ask.

## Examples

```text
# Figma label: "Lorem ipsum"
✅ "Lorem ipsum"
❌ "Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit."

# User shares a heading with no body copy
✅ Ask: "Should this section have body copy, or stay heading-only?"
❌ Invent a paragraph of marketing text.

# Unknown API behavior
✅ Inspect the code or ask the user.
❌ Assume endpoint shape or error handling without evidence.
```

## Why

Invented content creates review churn, breaks design fidelity, and hides missing requirements. Asking early is faster than undoing guessed work.
